      <hedline>
        <hl1>Mosquito Madness</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Jack Acree letter says West Nile Virus is one of lesser dangers in New York City</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>I've been observing the frenzy regarding the West Nile virus bemusedly. In an Aug. 1 Op-Ed article about West Nile, Paul W. Ewald mentions dengue fever, a mosquito-borne illness that I contracted in 1998 while living in Honduras. In Honduras, dengue is nicknamed ''break-bone fever,'' since that is what it feels like when you have it. I endured fevers from 101 to 105 degrees for more than a week, but on the plus side I lost 20 pounds in seven days.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>I've been observing the frenzy regarding the West Nile virus bemusedly. In an Aug. 1 Op-Ed article about West Nile, Paul W. Ewald mentions dengue fever, a mosquito-borne illness that I contracted in 1998 while living in Honduras. In Honduras, dengue is nicknamed ''break-bone fever,'' since that is what it feels like when you have it. I endured fevers from 101 to 105 degrees for more than a week, but on the plus side I lost 20 pounds in seven days.</p>
        <p>I'm no fan of mosquitoes, but I don't fear them. I sleep with my screenless windows open on these wonderfully cool nights. I wonder how many of those concerned about West Nile stand off the curb while waiting to cross the street or leave their seat belts unbuckled in taxis? I have a better idea where the real danger lies in New York.</p>
        <p>JACK ACREE  New York, Aug. 1, 2000</p>
      </block>
